evelopment itself as a post-World War II sociopolitical ideological formation, critiques related policies, and explores the various uses of the concept of the "indigenous" in several discursive contexts. Gupta begins with an analysis of the connections and conflicts between the world food economy, transnational capital, and technological innovations in wheat production. He then examines narratives of village politics in Alipur to show how certain discourses influenced governmental policies on the green revolution. Drawing links between village life, national trends, and global forces, Gupta concludes with a discussion of the implications of environmentalism as exemplified by the Rio Earth Summit and an examination of how global environmental treaties may detrimentally affect the lives of subaltern peoples.With a series of subtle observations on rural politics, nationalism, gender, modernization, and difference, this innovative study capitalizes on many different disciplines: anthropology, sociology, comparative politics, cultural geography, ecology, political science, agricultural economics, and history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aAgriculture and statezIndiazAliÌ#x84;pura. 0aAgriculture and statezIndiazAlīpura. 0aAgriculture and statezIndiazAlīpura. 0aAgriculturezIndiazAliÌ#x84;pura. 0aAgriculturezIndiazAlīpura. 0aAgriculturezIndiazAlīpura. 0aEnvironmental policyzIndiazAliÌ#x84;pura. 0aEnvironmental policyzIndiazAlīpura. 0aEnvironmental policyzIndiazAlīpura. 0aEthnosciencezIndiazAliÌ#x84;pura. 0aEthnosciencezIndiazAlīpura. 0aEthnosciencezIndiazAlīpura. 0aRural developmentzIndiazAliÌ#x84;pura. 0aRural developmentzIndiazAlīpura. 0aRural developmentzIndiazAlīpura. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Economy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gruyte